A {{ill|Mune-fuda|ja|棟札}} dated {{ill|August 14|ja|8月14日}}, 880 (Gangyō 4) still exists at the shrine, serving as historical evidence of its construction.<ref name="choushi">額田町史、pp.188-189</ref> This plaque predates others such as the one from {{ill|1122|ja|1122年}} ({{ill|Hōan|ja|保安}} 3) at {{ill|Chūson-ji|ja|中尊寺}}.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E6%A3%9F%E6%9C%AD-140683 |title=棟札とは |publisher=コトバンク |accessdate=2013-01-21}}</ref> However, the exact date is debated due to questions about its authenticity.<ref name="choushi"/> The plaque was exhibited at the {{ill|Nagoya Pan-Pacific Peace Exposition|ja|名古屋汎太平洋平和博覧会}} in {{ill|1937|ja|1937年}} ({{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和}} 12).<ref name="choushi"/>

In {{ill|1894|ja|1894年}} (Meiji 27), the current main hall, built in {{ill|Nagare-zukuri|ja|流造}} style, was constructed. The Kaguraden was added in {{ill|1935|ja|1935年}} (Shōwa 10).<ref name="rekishiteki-219-232"/>

A ceremony celebrating the completion of a new worship hall was held on {{ill|October 20|ja|10月20日}}, {{ill|2012|ja|2012年}} (Heisei 24).

