On {{ill|October 3|ja|10月3日|12=draft}} of {{ill|1872|ja|1872nd year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|12=draft}} 5), it was designated as a {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|12=draft}} under the {{ill|Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|12=draft}}.<ref name="gunshi"/> It is regarded as a shrine dedicated to the ancestor deity of {{ill|Nukata District|ja|額田郡|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://okazaki-kanko.jp/event/682 | title=夏山八幡宮火まつり |website=岡崎おでかけナビ |publisher=岡崎市観光協会 |date= | accessdate=2022-1-5 }}</ref>

A {{ill|Mune-fuda|ja|棟札|12=draft}} dated {{ill|August 14|ja|8月14日|12=draft}}, 880 (Gangyō 4) still exists at the shrine, serving as historical evidence of its construction.<ref name="choushi">額田町史、pp.188-189</ref> This plaque predates others such as the one from {{ill|1122|ja|1122nd year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Hōan|ja|保安|12=draft}} 3) at {{ill|Chūson-ji|ja|中尊寺|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E6%A3%9F%E6%9C%AD-140683 |title=棟札とは |publisher=コトバンク |accessdate=2013-01-21}}</ref> However, the exact date is debated due to questions about its authenticity.<ref name="choushi"/> The plaque was exhibited at the {{ill|Nagoya Pan-Pacific Peace Exposition|ja|名古屋汎太平洋平和博覧会|12=draft}} in {{ill|1937|ja|1937th year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和|12=draft}} 12).<ref name="choushi"/>

In {{ill|1894|ja|1894th year|12=draft}} (Meiji 27), the current main hall, built in {{ill|Nagare-zukuri|ja|流造|12=draft}} style, was constructed. The Kaguraden was added in {{ill|1935|ja|1935th year|12=draft}} (Shōwa 10).<ref name="rekishiteki-219-232"/>

A ceremony celebrating the completion of a new worship hall was held on {{ill|October 20|ja|10月20日|12=draft}}, {{ill|2012|ja|2012nd year|12=draft}} (Heisei 24).

